`crates/steno/tests` is the integration-test suite for the `steno` crate's public API — parsing, count/type expansion, rendering (plain/smart/snippet/struct), stroke encoding, and the C++/Neovim integration boundaries. Depending on this directory buys confidence that the whole pipeline (`parse_source` → `expand_counts`/`expand_types` → render/emit) produces correct, corpus-validated output; nothing here is reused by library code.

The dominant coupling is that most files load the real `dict.steno` (or `dict.infinite.steno`) from the repo root via `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`-relative paths (`../../dict.steno`), rather than fixtures — editing that corpus (renaming/removing strokes, changing counts/arities/flags) can silently break tests across `blocks.rs`, `expand.rs`, `expand_types.rs`, `parse_source.rs`, `render.rs`, `smart.rs`, `snippet.rs`, `stroke_order.rs`, and `infinite.rs` simultaneously, since each hardcodes specific stroke names and corpus-size thresholds (e.g. >70 entries, >1000 snippet keys). Several files (`smart.rs`, `snippet.rs`) had to hand-synthesize a `TypedEntry`/`Entry` for stroke `STKWR-LT` after the corpus repurposed it, rather than dropping that coverage — a precedent to follow if the corpus changes again underneath other tests. `cpp_check.rs` and `infinite.rs` both exercise the `dict.infinite.steno` type-system path and pin it against C++ and against `expand_dict` respectively — the differential pins (`walker_matches_expand_dict_on_enumerable_subset`, `cpp_dictionary_matches_reference_walker`) mean changing Pass A/B or the walker requires checking both.

`parse_source.rs`/`parse_template.rs` pin the grammar and exact error-message substrings; `expand.rs`/`expand_types.rs` pin Pass A/B semantics; `render.rs`/`smart.rs`/`snippet.rs`/`blocks.rs` pin the three render profiles plus struct-literal emission; `stroke.rs`/`stroke_order.rs` pin stroke encoding and corpus ordering hygiene; `landing_reuse.rs` guards a specific LSP snippet-dedup bug; `editor.rs` specs the editor-simulation/serialization layer standalone; `nvim_plugin.rs` and `cpp_check.rs` are the only files reaching outside the Rust pipeline (headless Neovim, C++ toolchain), both tolerating environment absence by skipping rather than failing.

Invariant spanning the suite: any test reading `dict.steno`/`dict.infinite.steno` must tolerate corpus growth but treat specific hardcoded strokes/counts as contract — if a change is intentional, all files referencing that stroke need updating together, not just the one that failed first.

No intent.md is present, so no divergence can be assessed.